caption: Food was pretty good, rice lacked some flavor...just tasted the butter, it really felt like something was missing. Typically I dont need to put anything on my rice to really enjoy the dish. However, everything else was good. Lamb prepared to perfection and salad fresh.

After hearing the neighbors talk about how much they love this place I decided to pop in and grab a falafel sandwich on Sunday afternoon. I was waiting on by a very friendly bartender. We chatted away while I waited for my sandwiches.  I talked about how I look forward to going there now that you can eat either inside or now that it's getting warmer and we can eat outside.  We ate our falafel sandwiches in the car because we were in a rush. It was quite good. We love the french fries. They are the kind that are battered and fried. I made sure to grab them out of the packaging right away so they were nice and crisp. My mother was more sensible and had her falafel sandwich with a salad and she said that was quite good too.  Looking forward to trying more of the menu of that the bartender was encouraging me to have!
The food is amazing here and the service is one of a kind too. I've been ordering here for the past year and I can't have enough of their food.

The best high class mediterranean food in brooklyn. The manu is short and to the point. The service is top notch. I don't care for drinks and there is a bar with high chairs with a barman. Management is very accommodating.

Wandered in early on a wintry night. Were out of our normal neighborhood but felt a friendly warm vibe. We ordered the mixed vegetarian platter and the mixed grill to share. Knew we had a winner at the first bite of the hot crispy chickpea falafel. All the dips, mezzes and veg were fresh, and the meat grilled to perfection. The Egyptian owner Jimmy is vivacious and lovely (when my wife mentioned enjoying foul, a popular Egyptian bean dish, he made her some on the spot “for breakfast”). Loyal longtime customers were piling in every few minutes for takeaway. It’s that perfect mix: a 16 year old local joint that’s a cut above. We’ll be back.

I love middle eastern food.  A tray full of middle eastern appetizers is my idea of the perfect meal.  I passed by Mazzat on Columbia Street for years and never went inside.  I never saw more than a few people in there so it couldn't be very good, right?  What I didn't understand was that Mazzat has such a loyal following in the neighborhood that most of its business was delivery.  My favorite middle eastern food in the city is at Tanoreen in Bay Ridge. It's also rated by NY Mag as the #1 middle eastern restaurant in NYC.  Well, Mazzat comes very close and, in fact, surpasses it with some of its dishes.  Their hummus is the best I've had anywhere. Their rice is addictive.  I love their mixed grilled platter.  Bacon-wrapped dates, sujuk, baba ganoush, tabouili... all first rate.  Robby and Jimmy, the owners, are affable guys, eager to please.  It also has a large, well-stocked bar and is a popular place for world cup viewing.
